# [WEBTRANS](../wg/webtrans.html)

## Summary
The WEBTRANS working group met at IETF 125 to discuss the status of core protocol drafts and coordination with the W3C WebTransport working group. The primary focus was the announcement of Working Group Last Call (WGLC) for the three main documents: [draft-ietf-webtrans-overview](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-webtrans-overview/), [draft-ietf-webtrans-http3](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-webtrans-http3/), and [draft-ietf-webtrans-http2](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-webtrans-http2/). Technical discussions centered on HTTP status code semantics for unsupported resources and updates on interoperability testing.

## Key Discussion Points

### W3C WebTransport Update
**Will Law** presented an update on the W3C WebTransport API (Slides: [IETF125 slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-webtrans-ietf125-slides-00), Slide 2).
*   A new working draft was published on February 4, 2024. The group is targeting a release candidate by mid-2024 and finalization in 2026.
*   Recent changes include integration with the Fetch API, which enables header support—a highly requested feature.
*   WebTransport has been selected as an **Interop 2026** focus area by major browser vendors, which is expected to significantly improve cross-browser compatibility.
*   The W3C spec is moving into the "wide review" phase.

### Protocol Drafts and WGLC
**Eric Kinnear** provided updates on the IETF drafts (Slides: [IETF125 slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-webtrans-ietf125-slides-00), Slide 8).

*   **[draft-ietf-webtrans-overview](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-webtrans-overview/):** Editorial cleanup completed; no open technical issues.
*   **[draft-ietf-webtrans-http3](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-webtrans-http3/):**
    *   Security considerations updated regarding server-initiated streams and resource limits.
    *   `MAX_SESSIONS` has been removed as previously decided.
    *   The `SETTINGS_WEBTRANSPORT_MAX_SESSIONS` is now server-only (except for draft version negotiation).
    *   New error codes added: `WEBTRANSPORT_ALPN_ERROR` and `WEBTRANSPORT_REQUIREMENTS_NOT_MET`.
    *   Guidance added on the capsule-based protocol, emphasizing that native H3 streams should be preferred.
*   **[draft-ietf-webtrans-http2](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-webtrans-http2/):**
    *   Security and flow control updates parallel to the H3 draft.
    *   Alignment of error code sizes with H3.
    *   Split settings for initial max stream data into local and remote variants to match QUIC semantics.

### Discussion: HTTP Status Codes for Unsupported Resources
A technical discussion occurred regarding the appropriate HTTP status code to return when a resource exists but does not support WebTransport.
*   **Lucas Pardue** noted that 406 (Not Acceptable) is technically for media types and might be inappropriate.
*   **Christian Huitema** raised privacy concerns and asked how to handle authenticated clients who are denied WebTransport access.
*   **Mike Bishop** suggested 403 (Forbidden) is sufficient if the denial is based on identity, but noted 405 (Method Not Allowed) is technically incorrect as the method (CONNECT) is allowed, just not the protocol.
*   **Ben Schwartz** (quoting Mark Nottingham) suggested using a generic 4xx code rather than over-specifying, as implementers should follow existing HTTP RFCs.
*   **Ted Hardie** and **Colin Jones** argued that providing a unique signal to the client is necessary for interoperability and to prevent client confusion.
*   **Lucas Pardue** suggested looking into "Problem Details" (RFC 9457) or specific header fields to clarify the error.

### Interoperability Testing
**Martin Seemann** presented updates on the WebTransport Interop Runner (Slides: [IETF125 slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-webtrans-ietf125-slides-00), Slide 23).
*   The runner now includes four implementations: Chrome, Firefox, WebTransport Go, and one additional server.
*   Current test cases cover the handshake, ALPN negotiation, uni/bidirectional streams, and datagrams.
*   Future tests will include multiplexing, stream resets (including partially reliable resets), and connection close capsules.

## Decisions and Action Items
*   **Working Group Last Call (WGLC):** WGLC is officially open for [draft-ietf-webtrans-overview](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-webtrans-overview/), [draft-ietf-webtrans-http3](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-webtrans-http3/), and [draft-ietf-webtrans-http2](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-webtrans-http2/).
*   **Action Item:** The chairs and editors will consult with the HTTP Directorate regarding the best practice for status codes when an extended CONNECT sub-protocol is unsupported.
*   **Action Item:** Martin Seemann to share pointers/links for the Interop Runner Docker requirements to the mailing list to encourage more implementations.

## Next Steps
*   Participants are encouraged to conduct a full review of the documents during the WGLC period.
*   The working group will monitor the progress of the "Reliable Resets" (QUIC) dependency, as it is required for the finalization of the H3 draft.
*   The chairs will evaluate the results of the WGLC to determine if a second last call or immediate progression to the IESG is warranted.